{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17627329","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17627329"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:22+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T16:47:22+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17115"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17115","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17115"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.29,0.15,0.05,0.41]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9805"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77005"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9805","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9805"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17115"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62511"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5013"},{"type":"tags","id":"5048"},{"type":"tags","id":"9838"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22983"},{"type":"contributions","id":"23092"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77005","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77005"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 65-year-old woman with atrial fibrillation is prescribed dipyridamole as part of her antiplatelet therapy.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of dipyridamole?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Blocks voltage-gated calcium channels in platelets","Inhibits P2Y12 receptors on platelet membranes","Antagonises thromboxane A2 receptor signalling","Blocks cyclooxygenase-1 enzyme in platelets","Inhibits phosphodiesterase and adenosine uptake"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits phosphodiesterase and adenosine uptake\u003C/strong\u003E are the primary mechanisms of dipyridamole. This dual mechanism results in:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased intracellular cyclic AMP through phosphodiesterase inhibition\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003EIncreased extracellular adenosine through reuptake blockade\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThese changes lead to vasodilation and reduced platelet aggregation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect mechanisms can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks voltage-gated calcium channels in platelets\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of calcium channel blockers like nifedipine, verapamil and diltiazem. These medicines reduce calcium influx into smooth muscle cells, causing vasodilation.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibits P2Y12 receptors on platelet membranes\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of P2Y12 inhibitors like clopidogrel and ticagrelor. These medicines prevent platelet activation by blocking ADP binding.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonises thromboxane A2 receptor signalling\u003C/strong\u003E would prevent platelet aggregation by blocking thromboxane signalling, but this is not how dipyridamole works.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks cyclooxygenase-1 enzyme in platelets\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of aspirin, which prevents thromboxane A2 synthesis in platelets.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe increased adenosine and cyclic AMP levels caused by dipyridamole make it useful both as an antiplatelet agent and as a coronary vasodilator for cardiac stress testing. The vasodilatory effect is particularly useful in stress testing as it can reveal coronary artery disease by creating a \u0027steal\u0027 phenomenon.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dipyridamole inhibits phosphodiesterase and blocks adenosine reuptake, leading to increased intracellular cyclic AMP and extracellular adenosine.","The primary effects of dipyridamole are vasodilation and inhibition of platelet aggregation.","Dipyridamole is used clinically as an antiplatelet agent and in cardiac stress testing."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62511"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17115"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62511","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62511"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-05T22:13:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-05T22:14:47+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9805"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77005"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"update